WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:10.549
Prof: We're discussing
the fertility transition and

00:00:10.549 --> 00:00:17.170
we've talked that prior to the
fertility transition there was

00:00:17.170 --> 00:00:22.130
control of fertility,
but it was at a very high level.

00:00:22.130 --> 00:00:28.253
In different parts of the world
we talked in very general terms

00:00:28.253 --> 00:00:29.340
about it.
 

00:00:29.340 --> 00:00:33.336
I want to just describe a
little bit about what the story

00:00:33.336 --> 00:00:36.119
was in Europe,
exactly how fertility was

00:00:36.119 --> 00:00:37.190
controlled.
 

00:00:37.190 --> 00:00:40.586
One of the main reasons,
I mentioned this before,

00:00:40.586 --> 00:00:44.550
but didn't really describe it,
is control of marriage.

00:00:44.550 --> 00:00:48.042
That the number of people that
were allowed to,

00:00:48.042 --> 00:00:51.231
and in some sense,
get married changed with

00:00:51.231 --> 00:00:55.180
economic conditions and
agricultural conditions.

00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:59.293
You can see that very clearly
wherever you get statistics from

00:00:59.293 --> 00:01:00.170
the period.
 

00:01:00.170 --> 00:01:03.792
As you know,
the first year of the Black

00:01:03.792 --> 00:01:08.506
Death was 1347-1348,
and huge numbers of people died

00:01:08.506 --> 00:01:13.409
and their land was immediately
taken over by someone else.

00:01:13.409 --> 00:01:16.970
Immediately these new
landowners got married.

00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:19.840
There was an enormous burst of
marriage.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:23.706
Like in one small French
village there had been 10 to 12

00:01:23.706 --> 00:01:26.730
marriages a year in the
preceding decade.

00:01:26.730 --> 00:01:31.870
In 1349, the first year after
that phase of the plague passed

00:01:31.870 --> 00:01:35.125
it went from 10 to 12,
to 86 marriages,

00:01:35.125 --> 00:01:37.010
an enormous thing.
 

00:01:37.010 --> 00:01:42.312
What was going on is there
was--before the Black Death when

00:01:42.312 --> 00:01:47.524
Europe was crowded for its
system there was a huge pool of

00:01:47.524 --> 00:01:53.010
unmarried individuals who really
wanted to get married,

00:01:53.010 --> 00:01:58.197
but did not have any land on
which to support themselves or a

00:01:58.197 --> 00:02:03.125
family and the opening of the
land allows marriage to take

00:02:03.125 --> 00:02:03.989
place.
 

00:02:03.989 --> 00:02:07.879
Then not only did they get
married right away,

00:02:07.879 --> 00:02:11.218
but the women got pregnant
immediately,

00:02:11.218 --> 00:02:13.150
and one contemporary observer
wrote,

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:16.219
"There are pregnant women
wherever you look."

00:02:16.219 --> 00:02:19.568
This is 1349.
 

00:02:19.568 --> 00:02:24.568
Up--this fertility rate was a
flexible system that moved up

00:02:24.568 --> 00:02:29.740
and down according to economic
and demographic conditions.

00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:33.848
In England, there's data from
the 1550s and later,

00:02:33.848 --> 00:02:37.199
the gross reproduction rate,
that's the number of women--

00:02:37.199 --> 00:02:40.974
there are a certain number of
women in one generation how many

00:02:40.974 --> 00:02:43.080
female children do they produce?
 

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:47.179
In the 1550s it was 2.8,
so one will reproduce a woman,

00:02:47.179 --> 00:02:51.203
the gross reproduction rate
will be one, but they were

00:02:51.203 --> 00:02:52.568
producing 2.8.
 

00:02:52.568 --> 00:02:58.830
A century later it drops down
to 1.8 and that's the 1650s,

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:02.568
and by 1880s it rises again to
over three,

00:03:02.568 --> 00:03:07.060
so there's enormous range
between one,

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:09.254
close to one,
less than two,

00:03:09.254 --> 00:03:13.646
just reproducing themselves
getting into this dangerous

00:03:13.646 --> 00:03:16.554
thing where--
with the very high death rates,

00:03:16.554 --> 00:03:19.210
where the whole society at that
rate won't continue--

00:03:19.210 --> 00:03:29.169
and a factor of three women
which will do just fine.

00:03:29.169 --> 00:03:32.034
You can see the same thing at
the age of marriage,

00:03:32.034 --> 00:03:35.133
not only the numbers of
marriage of course but the age

00:03:35.133 --> 00:03:36.068
of marriage.
 

00:03:36.068 --> 00:03:39.260
During the early 1800s remember
that was a time when the

00:03:39.260 --> 00:03:43.044
American food is there,
European population was rising,

00:03:43.044 --> 00:03:46.860
strong as a high birth rate so
land hunger became--

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:50.301
land--there was no extra land
available so marriage became

00:03:50.301 --> 00:03:54.282
later and later,
and eventually reached 23 to 28

00:03:54.282 --> 00:03:58.669
for females and even older than
that for males.

00:03:58.669 --> 00:04:03.658
By that time probably the
average lifespan was 35,

00:04:03.658 --> 00:04:08.030
it had improved some,
but if you're fertile at say 15

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:12.354
and you don't marry until 28,
that's a huge chunk of your

00:04:12.354 --> 00:04:15.318
reproductive life where you're
not reproducing,

00:04:15.318 --> 00:04:20.569
that reduces the birth rate and
keeps the population in check.

00:04:20.569 --> 00:04:26.389
However, once in marriage,
the children just flowed.

00:04:26.389 --> 00:04:30.127
There was no--apparently no
control within marriage

00:04:30.127 --> 00:04:31.100
whatsoever.
 

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:36.521
In 300 years--all the data that
we have says that in 300 years

00:04:36.521 --> 00:04:42.120
in Europe there was no control
of fertility within marriage,

00:04:42.120 --> 00:04:44.697
all the control,
all the social control of

00:04:44.697 --> 00:04:47.779
population was in how many
people got married,

00:04:47.779 --> 00:04:51.934
what they called the nuptiality;
the fraction of people that got

00:04:51.934 --> 00:04:55.660
married was the total mechanism
of social control.

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:59.259
There's of course external
control by disease,

00:04:59.259 --> 00:05:02.810
by famines because some plague
of the plants,

00:05:02.810 --> 00:05:06.704
and then there were individual
controls which we've talked

00:05:06.704 --> 00:05:08.959
about infanticide and so forth.
 

00:05:08.959 --> 00:05:12.470
In terms of social controls,
the northwestern--

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:16.338
the Northern Europeans,
especially northwestern

00:05:16.338 --> 00:05:20.882
European model was controlled
marriage and it was quite

00:05:20.882 --> 00:05:22.060
effective.
 

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:26.148
These marriage controls didn't
just happen automatically,

00:05:26.148 --> 00:05:30.382
people just didn't sort of have
a rational sense that said,

00:05:30.382 --> 00:05:32.500
'Oh I can't get married.'
 

00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:34.930
There was really--the controls
were forced upon them.

00:05:34.930 --> 00:05:41.053
Most land was owned by some
landowner and the man was given

00:05:41.053 --> 00:05:44.959
a plot of land which he could
work.

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:48.329
It was the size so that one
individual could work this plot

00:05:48.329 --> 00:05:48.910
of land.
 

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:51.990
He starts having children.
 

00:05:51.990 --> 00:05:56.997
Well the landlord knows that
only one son is needed to farm

00:05:56.997 --> 00:06:01.966
that land,
and the father knows he can

00:06:01.966 --> 00:06:08.937
only give that land to one son,
so there's tremendous pressure

00:06:08.937 --> 00:06:12.870
if you have extra children they
can't stay at home.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:15.290
You'll see when we talk about
China a very different model.

00:06:15.290 --> 00:06:18.394
He can't stay at home,
those people are forced off to

00:06:18.394 --> 00:06:20.992
the cities,
and in the cities are very

00:06:20.992 --> 00:06:23.569
dangerous and disease ridden
places,

00:06:23.569 --> 00:06:27.714
so they just die in the cities,
and the cities are growing this

00:06:27.714 --> 00:06:31.259
time but very high death rates
still in the cities.

00:06:31.259 --> 00:06:34.745
About one-third,
each generation had to be

00:06:34.745 --> 00:06:40.103
replenished as I've mentioned to
you, but about one-third in the

00:06:40.103 --> 00:06:41.040
cities.
 

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:44.795
The landlord of course didn't
want these extra children around

00:06:44.795 --> 00:06:48.367
because he would have more and
more people to feed with the

00:06:48.367 --> 00:06:52.310
same amount of land therefore
the same amount of production.

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:56.137
You had to get the landlord's
permission in order to get

00:06:56.137 --> 00:07:00.521
married and if you didn't--if he
didn't have extra land for you,

00:07:00.521 --> 00:07:02.540
you couldn't get married.
 

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:05.173
Of course officially it wasn't
the landlord but it was the

00:07:05.173 --> 00:07:07.670
local parish church that you had
to get married in,

00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:11.399
but guess who hired the parish
minister or priest?

00:07:11.399 --> 00:07:14.970
The local landlord,
and the whole structure of

00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:19.651
churches almost everywhere is
that they are very much either

00:07:19.651 --> 00:07:23.699
controlled by or mutual support
of the gentry,

00:07:23.699 --> 00:07:30.009
the rich people and the
religious authorities intermix.

00:07:30.009 --> 00:07:34.172
They weren't allowed to get
married either by the landlord

00:07:34.172 --> 00:07:35.560
or by the church.
 

00:07:35.560 --> 00:07:37.598
It was very--you had to post
what they called banns so

00:07:37.598 --> 00:07:39.100
everybody knew there was a
marriage,

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:40.819
and of course the landlord
would notice,

00:07:40.819 --> 00:07:47.470
and so it was impossible to do
anything about that.

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:52.170
Another mechanism was going off
and becoming a servant that was

00:07:52.170 --> 00:07:55.430
one of the very standard kinds
of things.

00:07:55.430 --> 00:08:01.009
They would leave home very
young become a servant and--

00:08:01.009 --> 00:08:03.660
males and females both servants
in the houses,

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:07.009
you've all seen these Victorian
movies and earlier movies,

00:08:07.009 --> 00:08:08.920
how many servants they have.
 

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:11.579
Of course they were never
allowed to get married,

00:08:11.579 --> 00:08:14.278
not allowed to have sex,
no boyfriend,

00:08:14.278 --> 00:08:15.949
no girlfriend,
none of that was allowed--

00:08:15.949 --> 00:08:19.564
very, very strict rules on
house servants and house

00:08:19.564 --> 00:08:23.759
servants were a very large
faction of the young people--

00:08:23.759 --> 00:08:30.399
of everybody in, say, England.
 

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:33.711
Then those that didn't become
servants would go off and become

00:08:33.711 --> 00:08:34.580
an apprentice.
 

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:38.009
One son stays at home,
the others go off and become

00:08:38.009 --> 00:08:40.995
apprentices,
and apprenticeship was a very

00:08:40.995 --> 00:08:45.041
long period of time in which
they had to learn the skills and

00:08:45.041 --> 00:08:48.547
get some sort of resources so
that they could buy the

00:08:48.547 --> 00:08:53.200
equipment and rent the shop and
set up eventually on their own,

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:58.506
or wait until the master died
and then inherit the master's

00:08:58.506 --> 00:08:59.240
place.
 

00:08:59.240 --> 00:09:03.532
The end result of all this is
that it took many,

00:09:03.532 --> 00:09:08.736
many years to establish a
sufficient economic base so that

00:09:08.736 --> 00:09:13.029
the society would allow you to
get married.

00:09:13.029 --> 00:09:17.721
Many people never got married;
I'll show you a little bit

00:09:17.721 --> 00:09:21.609
later what the marriage rates
actually were in Europe during

00:09:21.609 --> 00:09:24.309
this period, and its
surprisingly low.

00:09:24.309 --> 00:09:26.370
The culture adapts to this.
 

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:30.029
What do all these unmarried men
and women do?

00:09:30.029 --> 00:09:35.192
We have the spinster woman;
we have the confirmed bachelor,

00:09:35.192 --> 00:09:38.551
again you've seen men in much
British comedy and British

00:09:38.551 --> 00:09:40.711
movies about--
always has characters in it

00:09:40.711 --> 00:09:44.490
where some confirmed bachelor,
he's just not getting married.

00:09:44.490 --> 00:09:48.620
Presumably a fair amount of the
homosexuality that was present,

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:51.979
especially in the British upper
classes is due to this whole

00:09:51.979 --> 00:09:55.509
tradition that a lot of males
are not going to get married,

00:09:55.509 --> 00:09:59.289
and then they do something with
their sexual impulse.

00:09:59.289 --> 00:10:03.524
Of course that's not proven;
we don't really understand the

00:10:03.524 --> 00:10:05.928
basis of homosexuality.
 

00:10:05.928 --> 00:10:08.820
Females were also,
like the males,

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:12.494
forced off the land,
if they were not the wife of

00:10:12.494 --> 00:10:15.480
the one son that inherited the
land,

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:18.427
they had to go somewhere else
so they went to the cities where

00:10:18.427 --> 00:10:22.717
there were not jobs,
especially not jobs for women

00:10:22.717 --> 00:10:27.870
so they become sort of a
floating population,

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:31.942
very largely prostitutes--huge
explosion of prostitution at

00:10:31.942 --> 00:10:36.157
this time both because of the
excess women that are trying to

00:10:36.157 --> 00:10:39.740
stay alive that have migrated
into the cities,

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:44.671
and there's all these bachelors
there having some sort of job

00:10:44.671 --> 00:10:47.629
that could pay for their
services.

00:10:47.629 --> 00:10:54.970
Of course you know that babies
that resulted from any of these

00:10:54.970 --> 00:11:02.190
situations were very often just
abandoned and left to die.

00:11:02.190 --> 00:11:07.129
This control of marriage,
that marriage was the control,

00:11:07.129 --> 00:11:11.341
the social control on
population lasted well into the

00:11:11.341 --> 00:11:14.283
1800s,
well into and possibly even

00:11:14.283 --> 00:11:16.500
through the Victorian era.
 

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:20.149
These mechanisms together
reduced the north European

00:11:20.149 --> 00:11:24.442
birthrate, and especially in
England, to about 50% of what it

00:11:24.442 --> 00:11:26.590
otherwise could have been.
 

00:11:26.590 --> 00:11:31.023
Remember we did calculations of
how many children one can have,

00:11:31.023 --> 00:11:34.956
and then there's always
examples much to the high end of

00:11:34.956 --> 00:11:35.600
that.
 

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:39.196
But in England taking a
reasonable number,

00:11:39.196 --> 00:11:44.019
these controls of marriage cut
the birthrate in half.

00:11:44.019 --> 00:11:50.330
What did it feel like to the
people involved in this?

00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:56.070
I suspect a fair number of you
have heard this quote.

00:11:56.070 --> 00:12:00.158
It's a letter from a woman to
her uncle.

00:12:00.158 --> 00:12:03.490
Don't shout out but raise your
hand if you know it.

00:12:03.490 --> 00:12:06.990
"I think dearest uncle
that you cannot really wish me

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.509
to be the mother of a numerous
family,

00:12:09.509 --> 00:12:14.431
for I think you will see the
great inconvenience in a large

00:12:14.431 --> 00:12:17.908
family would be the hardship to
myself.

00:12:17.908 --> 00:12:22.075
Men never think what a hard
task it is for us women to go

00:12:22.075 --> 00:12:25.200
through this pregnancy very
often."

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:26.308
Have you heard this?
 

00:12:26.308 --> 00:12:28.500
No, no one's heard this letter,
it's very famous.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:31.629
This is a woman in this
situation.

00:12:31.629 --> 00:12:33.725
She's married,
and therefore she's having

00:12:33.725 --> 00:12:36.658
children one after the other
with no kind of control,

00:12:36.658 --> 00:12:39.114
and she's complaining,
'this is hard on me and why

00:12:39.114 --> 00:12:41.668
don't you men ever think how
hard this is on me?'

00:12:41.668 --> 00:12:44.270
What social class,
is this a poor woman,

00:12:44.270 --> 00:12:46.940
middle class woman,
upper class woman?

00:12:46.940 --> 00:12:54.340
Having all this--no ideas;
it's Queen Victoria.

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:57.279
Here's by far the richest woman
in the world,

00:12:57.279 --> 00:12:59.153
has all the help,
all the money,

00:12:59.153 --> 00:13:01.089
all the food,
and, even for her,

00:13:01.089 --> 00:13:04.322
it's a burden and she probably
doesn't have to do much of the

00:13:04.322 --> 00:13:07.340
burden except handle the
pregnancy and childbearing,

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:11.340
and if she perceives it as a
burden,

00:13:11.340 --> 00:13:14.860
then can you imagine what the
common woman thinks of it.

00:13:14.860 --> 00:13:22.988
By the way, it's Queen Victoria
to her uncle who is King Leopold

00:13:22.988 --> 00:13:28.019
of Belgium, you've heard this
before.

00:13:28.019 --> 00:13:44.836
When sexuality itself since--a
lot of problems with sexuality

00:13:44.836 --> 00:13:49.038
at that time.
 

00:13:49.038 --> 00:13:52.120
You've been reading some stuff
about it,

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:55.833
and one of the things is that
men, aside from the childbirth

00:13:55.833 --> 00:13:59.610
aspect of it that women were of
course always worried that if

00:13:59.610 --> 00:14:03.639
they had sex they would get
pregnant and often they didn't--

00:14:03.639 --> 00:14:06.928
usually they did not want to
get pregnant,

00:14:06.928 --> 00:14:12.120
but also the men were not very
skilled.

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:15.736
They either did not know how to
pleasure a woman,

00:14:15.736 --> 00:14:19.278
they didn't want to,
or they thought it was very

00:14:19.278 --> 00:14:22.668
improper to even try to pleasure
a woman.

00:14:22.668 --> 00:14:27.850
Here's another quote from Lady
Alice Huntington--

00:14:27.850 --> 00:14:31.846
Hillingdon--1857,
she died only in 1940 so we're

00:14:31.846 --> 00:14:36.269
really coming up to fairly
recent kinds of times,

00:14:36.269 --> 00:14:39.308
and presumably,
this was written in her journal

00:14:39.308 --> 00:14:39.970
in 1912.
 

00:14:39.970 --> 00:14:43.038
No one can find that journal so
they don't know the state of--

00:14:43.038 --> 00:14:46.879
how apocryphal this is,
but this is a quote that again

00:14:46.879 --> 00:14:50.870
you've probably heard,
at least part of it.

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:53.356
"I am happy now that
George,"

00:14:53.356 --> 00:14:55.975
her husband,
"calls on my bedchamber

00:14:55.975 --> 00:14:58.070
less frequently then of old.
 

00:14:58.070 --> 00:15:02.379
As it is, I now endure but two
calls a week and,

00:15:02.379 --> 00:15:04.980
when I hear his steps outside
my door,

00:15:04.980 --> 00:15:08.019
I lie down upon my bed,
close my eyes,

00:15:08.019 --> 00:15:12.220
open my legs and think of
England."

00:15:12.220 --> 00:15:15.586
Sometimes the quote is,
"think of Victoria,"

00:15:15.586 --> 00:15:18.700
but apparently think of England
is the proper--

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:21.532
again we're not talking about
some poor woman with a brutal

00:15:21.532 --> 00:15:25.159
husband,
as in some Oliver Twist movies,

00:15:25.159 --> 00:15:28.450
this is a very high status
lady.

00:15:28.450 --> 00:15:36.330
How did this change and who was
arrayed against this?

00:15:36.330 --> 00:15:40.690
People, women especially,
were not happy with the

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:41.779
situation.
 

00:15:41.779 --> 00:15:44.168
Young men of course wanted to
get married,

00:15:44.168 --> 00:15:47.647
couldn't until they were old,
and we've talked about that

00:15:47.647 --> 00:15:51.250
situation in Africa where the
bride price is very high,

00:15:51.250 --> 00:15:53.610
the old men control the bride
price,

00:15:53.610 --> 00:15:57.249
they don't allow the young men
to get married until there's

00:15:57.249 --> 00:15:58.629
almost a revolution.
 

00:15:58.629 --> 00:16:02.197
This is an aside,
but with respect to the bride

00:16:02.197 --> 00:16:07.082
price, we hear a lot about older
men marrying or having sex with

00:16:07.082 --> 00:16:08.480
younger women.
 

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:10.769
In the West it's one of the
things we sort of complain

00:16:10.769 --> 00:16:12.730
about,
about other cultures that this

00:16:12.730 --> 00:16:15.587
great disparity in age--
an older man with a younger

00:16:15.587 --> 00:16:15.990
woman.
 

00:16:15.990 --> 00:16:19.269
We tend to blame the man who's
getting married,

00:16:19.269 --> 00:16:22.048
but if you think of it from the
point of view of their society,

00:16:22.048 --> 00:16:24.908
that man has been under the
control of even older guys,

00:16:24.908 --> 00:16:28.193
the really powerful guys,
and so he's been abused and not

00:16:28.193 --> 00:16:30.538
allowed to get married until
he's old.

00:16:30.538 --> 00:16:33.471
The women of his age are
already married to the much

00:16:33.471 --> 00:16:35.769
older guys so this is his only
option.

00:16:35.769 --> 00:16:42.015
Again, within a society these
things all intermingle and form

00:16:42.015 --> 00:16:46.275
a pattern,
not necessarily a good pattern,

00:16:46.275 --> 00:16:50.870
not necessarily a pattern that
the people like,

00:16:50.870 --> 00:16:54.009
but it is a tight web.
 

00:16:54.009 --> 00:16:57.933
Coming back to Europe,
there was this unfortunate

00:16:57.933 --> 00:17:02.840
situation where young men
weren't allowed to get married,

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:04.390
young women weren't allowed to
get married,

00:17:04.390 --> 00:17:08.045
once you're in marriage the
sexual mores were so straight

00:17:08.045 --> 00:17:11.374
jacketed that it was not
pleasurable for most of the

00:17:11.374 --> 00:17:14.963
women apparently,
and who knows what the men were

00:17:14.963 --> 00:17:17.195
using,
the Victorian pornography

00:17:17.195 --> 00:17:20.078
during this period is lots of
mistresses,

00:17:20.078 --> 00:17:22.900
lots of prostitution and lots
of being whipped.

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:26.606
They loved to get punished
themselves, which is a

00:17:26.606 --> 00:17:30.855
surprising preponderance of
masochistic sexuality in the

00:17:30.855 --> 00:17:33.788
Victorian literature of that
time.

00:17:33.788 --> 00:17:38.618
At least from our point of
view, sexuality was a mess.

00:17:38.618 --> 00:17:39.868
So some people tried to change
this,

00:17:39.868 --> 00:17:43.980
of course there's always
pioneers, and in England one of

00:17:43.980 --> 00:17:46.818
the pioneers was a man and a
woman,

00:17:46.818 --> 00:17:50.190
Charles Bradlaugh and Annie
Besant.

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:55.782
In 1877 family planning
was--contraception was coming

00:17:55.782 --> 00:18:01.700
into possibility in England and
so they distributed--

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:05.432
printed and distributed what we
would now consider a very mild

00:18:05.432 --> 00:18:07.819
pamphlet about birth control
called,

00:18:07.819 --> 00:18:09.670
The Fruits of Philosophy.
 

00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:13.920
It was very abstract and
philosophical.

00:18:13.920 --> 00:18:15.519
Of course what happened to them?
 

00:18:15.519 --> 00:18:18.836
Arrested, indicted,
and the official indictment

00:18:18.836 --> 00:18:23.161
accused them of 'inciting and
encouraging the subjects of the

00:18:23.161 --> 00:18:26.777
Queen to indecent,
obscene, unnatural,

00:18:26.777 --> 00:18:30.698
and immoral practices,
and to bring them,' the

00:18:30.698 --> 00:18:33.500
citizens of the Queen,
the subjects of the Queen,

00:18:33.500 --> 00:18:37.430
'to a state of wickedness,
lewdness, and debauchery.'

00:18:37.430 --> 00:18:43.172
This is because they were
saying that--well there's these

00:18:43.172 --> 00:18:49.118
things called condoms around and
why don't you use them.

00:18:49.118 --> 00:18:52.263
This trial was very interesting
in that in a culture there's

00:18:52.263 --> 00:18:54.288
certain things you can't talk
about.

00:18:54.288 --> 00:18:57.273
If something is culturally
forbidden, like almost anything

00:18:57.273 --> 00:19:00.153
to do with sex in marriage,
you just couldn't talk about

00:19:00.153 --> 00:19:00.519
it.
 

00:19:00.519 --> 00:19:03.522
Now here's this big trial in
London, very famous,

00:19:03.522 --> 00:19:07.215
all the newspapers are carrying
it, and guess what everybody

00:19:07.215 --> 00:19:08.278
learns about?
 

00:19:08.278 --> 00:19:11.945
Birth control;
and a very big thing and some

00:19:11.945 --> 00:19:14.077
scholars,
some historians

00:19:14.077 --> 00:19:18.144
attribute--there's just the
period when the use of birth

00:19:18.144 --> 00:19:21.838
control is increasing
tremendously in England,

00:19:21.838 --> 00:19:23.808
-- and that this trial
popularized it.

00:19:23.808 --> 00:19:27.970
What did we have something
similar a few years ago in

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:30.288
America with our President?
 

00:19:30.288 --> 00:19:33.890
Bill Clinton and oral sex,
are you all too young to--

00:19:33.890 --> 00:19:37.604
that was a taboo topic,
you could not discuss it and

00:19:37.604 --> 00:19:40.873
then the right wing,
the conservatives who were

00:19:40.873 --> 00:19:44.365
opposed to this kind of free
sexual activity publicized it

00:19:44.365 --> 00:19:47.213
and publicized,
and publicized it until every

00:19:47.213 --> 00:19:50.583
teenager in America knew about
oral sex and now the data is

00:19:50.583 --> 00:19:54.009
that oral sex has just gone
exponentially down into the high

00:19:54.009 --> 00:19:56.450
schools and even junior high
schools.

00:19:56.450 --> 00:19:59.130
I could tell you stories about
that, but I won't.

00:19:59.130 --> 00:20:08.548
With all this moralizing about
it that the religious leaders,

00:20:08.548 --> 00:20:12.913
the political leaders,
the medical doctors said it was

00:20:12.913 --> 00:20:16.265
bad for you,
you've read some of that in

00:20:16.265 --> 00:20:19.345
your reading,
everybody is--they were

00:20:19.345 --> 00:20:21.250
terrorized in a sense.
 

00:20:21.250 --> 00:20:24.361
There was an intellectual
terrorization of the people,

00:20:24.361 --> 00:20:26.240
they feared legal prosecution.
 

00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:29.580
Most of these things were
illegal, to buy things,

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:31.946
to use things,
to write about them,

00:20:31.946 --> 00:20:33.338
to publish them.
 

00:20:33.338 --> 00:20:36.690
They were told that they would
get physical injury.

00:20:36.690 --> 00:20:40.816
You may have heard that
masturbation will make you blind

00:20:40.816 --> 00:20:45.318
and that--I don't know if any of
your parents said that but I

00:20:45.318 --> 00:20:47.118
heard it in my time.
 

00:20:47.118 --> 00:20:49.259
Mental injury,
if it doesn't make you blind,

00:20:49.259 --> 00:20:53.626
it'll make you crazy,
and deep moral reservations and

00:20:53.626 --> 00:20:58.916
just straight aesthetic distaste
that when the society frowns on

00:20:58.916 --> 00:21:03.703
something we sort of have
incorporated a kind of revulsion

00:21:03.703 --> 00:21:08.240
to anything which society
considers disgusting,

00:21:08.240 --> 00:21:11.750
and contraceptives themselves
were considered repulsive,

00:21:11.750 --> 00:21:16.308
unnatural, only for
prostitutes, that kind of thing.

00:21:16.308 --> 00:21:19.571
Of course, at that time,
almost--a lot of people were

00:21:19.571 --> 00:21:21.923
starting to do it,
but since you couldn't talk

00:21:21.923 --> 00:21:25.267
about it publicly,
no one knew what everyone else

00:21:25.267 --> 00:21:30.164
was doing so they thought they
had to take this great leap

00:21:30.164 --> 00:21:35.063
themselves in defiance of
everything that their culture is

00:21:35.063 --> 00:21:36.608
telling them.
 

00:21:36.608 --> 00:21:39.766
How did it--what happened an
individual's starting to think

00:21:39.766 --> 00:21:40.910
about these things.
 

00:21:40.910 --> 00:21:47.760
We have some interesting--a lot
of interesting stuff referred to

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:49.608
in the reading.
 

00:21:49.608 --> 00:21:52.868
Some of this in your reading is
letters to various pioneers,

00:21:52.868 --> 00:21:57.358
Margaret Sanger or who was it
in England the--

00:21:57.358 --> 00:21:59.650
I'm blocking on the name of the
clinic in England .

00:21:59.650 --> 00:22:04.593
We have letters from women sort
of begging information on how to

00:22:04.593 --> 00:22:07.338
keep from getting pregnant
again.

00:22:07.338 --> 00:22:10.304
A lot of it is not with any
official organizations,

00:22:10.304 --> 00:22:13.682
just women talking to women,
and some of it can be relaxed

00:22:13.682 --> 00:22:15.578
at a little bit later stage.
 

00:22:15.578 --> 00:22:21.246
There's a series of nice
interviews from the 1920s and

00:22:21.246 --> 00:22:27.232
1930s with elderly Italian and
Jewish women in the United

00:22:27.232 --> 00:22:28.410
States.
 

00:22:28.410 --> 00:22:31.880
They talked to each other about
technique,

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:33.940
because techniques is one of
the things,

00:22:33.940 --> 00:22:38.982
and this interview is from an
Italian American woman born in

00:22:38.982 --> 00:22:39.666
the U.S.
 

00:22:39.666 --> 00:22:44.282
in 1920, recent immigrant
parents, and the conversation

00:22:44.282 --> 00:22:47.190
took place in the late 1930s.
 

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:52.088
She works in a hair dressing
salon and she gets engaged,

00:22:52.088 --> 00:22:55.009
and of course all her coworkers
know about it,

00:22:55.009 --> 00:22:58.029
and so an interviewer--an
anthropologist--

00:22:58.029 --> 00:23:01.108
a sociologist--goes in and
starts asking her about it.

00:23:01.108 --> 00:23:04.119
Apparently prior to this little
quote they had brought up the

00:23:04.119 --> 00:23:06.630
topic of birth control so the
interviewer says,

00:23:06.630 --> 00:23:09.078
"How did you learn about
condoms?"

00:23:09.078 --> 00:23:13.636
Nina: "One of my customers
said, 'I really hope you don't

00:23:13.636 --> 00:23:16.700
get pregnant,
let him wear a raincoat.'

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:18.933
So I started wondering,
I'm thinking,

00:23:18.933 --> 00:23:22.532
I'm working and my mind just
can't work out what a raincoat

00:23:22.532 --> 00:23:23.338
is."
 

00:23:23.338 --> 00:23:27.876
Then Mary White who worked for
me said, "Baby what's on

00:23:27.876 --> 00:23:28.798
your mind?
 

00:23:28.798 --> 00:23:33.243
I said, "Mrs. Jacobs
said a funny thing to me,

00:23:33.243 --> 00:23:36.176
she said my ring was
lovely,"

00:23:36.176 --> 00:23:40.201
her marriage ring,
"but she hoped I didn't

00:23:40.201 --> 00:23:43.160
start a family and he should
wear a raincoat.

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:46.308
But I can't ask Johnny to wear
a raincoat to bed."

00:23:46.308 --> 00:23:50.366
This Mary White laughed and
laughed and says,

00:23:50.366 --> 00:23:54.608
"She means he's to wear a
condom."

00:23:54.608 --> 00:23:55.644
"What is it?"
 

00:23:55.644 --> 00:23:56.140
Nina said.
 

00:23:56.140 --> 00:24:00.042
And then she got told and got
enlightened in this and it's

00:24:00.042 --> 00:24:04.151
that kind of conversation where
individual people of not very

00:24:04.151 --> 00:24:08.191
high class are learning that
it's okay to buck the trend and

00:24:08.191 --> 00:24:12.298
even the basic information they
previously don't have.

00:24:12.298 --> 00:24:14.887
It doesn't always work out
that, when these discussions

00:24:14.887 --> 00:24:17.327
take place,
that the participants do take

00:24:17.327 --> 00:24:22.606
on the new behavior,
sometimes they don't want to do

00:24:22.606 --> 00:24:23.368
that.
 

00:24:23.368 --> 00:24:27.068
Gossip--most conversation by
humans is gossip and there's

00:24:27.068 --> 00:24:29.250
very good studies showing this.
 

00:24:29.250 --> 00:24:32.625
We know that from our chimps
days we're a very social

00:24:32.625 --> 00:24:34.980
species,
that status is so terribly

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:38.640
important and status translates
to social acceptability,

00:24:38.640 --> 00:24:42.066
so the purpose of gossip is to
find out what the limits of

00:24:42.066 --> 00:24:43.690
social acceptability are.
 

00:24:43.690 --> 00:24:46.730
Gossip is almost exclusively
about someone who has stepped

00:24:46.730 --> 00:24:49.984
over what was perceived to be
the limit and either gotten away

00:24:49.984 --> 00:24:52.118
with it or not gotten away with
it,

00:24:52.118 --> 00:24:54.980
or something that's now just
inside the limit.

00:24:54.980 --> 00:24:58.949
A large fraction of gossip is
to see what is socially

00:24:58.949 --> 00:25:02.136
acceptable in my circle,
and sometimes like we've seen

00:25:02.136 --> 00:25:04.117
here,
the use of condoms becomes

00:25:04.117 --> 00:25:07.930
socially acceptable as a result
of discussions like this.

00:25:07.930 --> 00:25:15.126
Sometimes it--at least this
individual at this time it

00:25:15.126 --> 00:25:18.930
doesn't become acceptable.
 

00:25:18.930 --> 00:25:23.598
Where is this other quote that
I'm looking for?

00:25:23.598 --> 00:25:26.670
This is another two women,
and the interviewer asks,

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:29.680
"How did your friends have
abortions?"

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:32.573
The issue of abortions came up
and as you probably have read or

00:25:32.573 --> 00:25:34.356
will read,
abortions at this time were

00:25:34.356 --> 00:25:37.769
very, very common,
all illegal, but very common.

00:25:37.769 --> 00:25:41.007
"Peggy,
I'm trying to think what they

00:25:41.007 --> 00:25:43.930
would take because they'd tell
me,

00:25:43.930 --> 00:25:47.077
a lot of them would have a
friend who would put something

00:25:47.077 --> 00:25:49.890
up there that would bring on
their period."

00:25:49.890 --> 00:25:52.118
The interviewer,
"A knitting needle?"

00:25:52.118 --> 00:25:53.828
Peggy, "No not a knitting
needle,

00:25:53.828 --> 00:25:57.969
some kind of fluid,
like hot boiling water or salt

00:25:57.969 --> 00:26:00.541
water,
they would ruin their insides,

00:26:00.541 --> 00:26:05.490
they would say,
'Oh Peggy don't you do that.'

00:26:05.490 --> 00:26:08.401
Oh no I would never do that,
that's my husband,

00:26:08.401 --> 00:26:10.680
it's the man who takes
care."

00:26:10.680 --> 00:26:15.421
It's interesting that in this
particular case it's usually the

00:26:15.421 --> 00:26:18.528
woman's responsibility in most
cases,

00:26:18.528 --> 00:26:21.355
but in this case whatever was
going on in the marriage she

00:26:21.355 --> 00:26:23.240
perceived it as the husband's
case,

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:27.809
and in further discussion that
it was his responsibility to use

00:26:27.809 --> 00:26:29.578
a condom all the time.
 

00:26:29.578 --> 00:26:36.420
The reason given by the woman
is not any moral consideration,

00:26:36.420 --> 00:26:40.009
no life--that's not the
consideration,

00:26:40.009 --> 00:26:43.229
but it's a medical thing,
it's just at that time the

00:26:43.229 --> 00:26:46.878
methods since it was illegal,
and if you didn't--even if you

00:26:46.878 --> 00:26:48.890
went to a practitioner it was
very,

00:26:48.890 --> 00:26:51.368
very dangerous but the kinds of
things that women actually used

00:26:51.368 --> 00:26:53.210
on themselves were so incredibly
dangerous,

00:26:53.210 --> 00:26:57.265
so the reason she's not having
an abortion is that she doesn't

00:26:57.265 --> 00:27:00.588
want to ruin herself in the
medical sort of way.

00:27:00.588 --> 00:27:04.108
You take this same woman,
transpose her 50 years later,

00:27:04.108 --> 00:27:07.420
where now abortion is safe and
possibly legal,

00:27:07.420 --> 00:27:11.088
this same woman may have a very
different attitude toward,

00:27:11.088 --> 00:27:14.720
but of course we don't know
anything about that.

00:27:14.720 --> 00:27:21.963
The point of this--series of
stories is a big change in

00:27:21.963 --> 00:27:25.715
culture,
that prior--every society has

00:27:25.715 --> 00:27:30.346
to control population in some
way and we've talked about the

00:27:30.346 --> 00:27:33.732
physical constraints,
the disease and famines,

00:27:33.732 --> 00:27:37.290
we've talked about the social
controls like not being able to

00:27:37.290 --> 00:27:40.384
get married,
but up until--in Europe up

00:27:40.384 --> 00:27:44.759
until very recently there was no
individual control.

00:27:44.759 --> 00:27:48.278
Individuals themselves did not
have the cultural freedom to

00:27:48.278 --> 00:27:50.220
make these kinds of decisions.
 

00:27:50.220 --> 00:27:53.820
Once married,
procreation just keeps going

00:27:53.820 --> 00:27:58.827
one after the other until either
someone dies or the woman

00:27:58.827 --> 00:28:00.759
becomes infertile.
 

00:28:00.759 --> 00:28:05.023
Now we're seeing a transition
where individuals can start

00:28:05.023 --> 00:28:08.640
deciding for themselves,
a very big change in the

00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:12.605
extension of agency that what a
person thinks they can control

00:28:12.605 --> 00:28:13.970
about their lives.
 

00:28:13.970 --> 00:28:22.482
Here is an elderly Jewish
woman, who was talking about her

00:28:22.482 --> 00:28:31.145
mother and said the way the
neighbors now start controlling

00:28:31.145 --> 00:28:34.489
this,
so the mother who did not use

00:28:34.489 --> 00:28:38.507
any kind of fertility control,
her friends and relatives would

00:28:38.507 --> 00:28:40.740
sort of get on her case but
mild,

00:28:40.740 --> 00:28:42.019
chided her mildly.
 

00:28:42.019 --> 00:28:44.009
When she would get pregnant
they would say,

00:28:44.009 --> 00:28:48.920
'Oh!, Esther not another
belly,' and so at this time

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:52.237
friends,
relatives, neighbors start

00:28:52.237 --> 00:28:54.930
imposing a new culture on you.
 

00:28:54.930 --> 00:29:00.509
There's some aspects of freedom
that the individual now gets to

00:29:00.509 --> 00:29:05.640
choose but the culture comes on
and now at least starts to

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:09.058
import a new cultural norm on
you.

00:29:09.058 --> 00:29:13.940
In Sicily, reputed to have very
high,

00:29:13.940 --> 00:29:15.818
actually having high fertility
rates,

00:29:15.818 --> 00:29:20.913
but at some point they go
through their transition and

00:29:20.913 --> 00:29:23.700
this is in 1980--
in the 1980s,

00:29:23.700 --> 00:29:28.132
very late, and this is a report
of woman who's one of the few

00:29:28.132 --> 00:29:30.940
remaining peasants in this
village.

00:29:30.940 --> 00:29:34.429
Sicily, like all the rest of
the world, is changing and

00:29:34.429 --> 00:29:35.269
growing up.
 

00:29:35.269 --> 00:29:39.152
She reported that these
families that still had child

00:29:39.152 --> 00:29:43.034
after child, after child,
their neighbors called them

00:29:43.034 --> 00:29:43.930
animals.
 

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:50.779
And this is Sicilian to
Sicilian.

00:29:50.779 --> 00:29:57.019
Here's another example of this,
a Jewish immigrant in the U.S.

00:29:57.019 --> 00:29:59.960
writing to her mother back in
Poland.

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:01.750
This is a lovely letter.
 

00:30:01.750 --> 00:30:05.150
"Here in America,
it is the custom that if a

00:30:05.150 --> 00:30:09.188
woman wants to she has a baby,
and if she does not want to

00:30:09.188 --> 00:30:11.028
have any, she doesn't.
 

00:30:11.028 --> 00:30:13.354
David's wife,
I don't know if that's a

00:30:13.354 --> 00:30:16.431
brother or something,
"David's wife says that

00:30:16.431 --> 00:30:19.068
she will have a baby every four
years.

00:30:19.068 --> 00:30:22.015
I think it is good to have one
every three years,

00:30:22.015 --> 00:30:24.960
and so after three years I
shall have another.

00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:28.036
It is terrible that at home
women suffer only hardships in

00:30:28.036 --> 00:30:29.170
childbearing."
 

00:30:29.170 --> 00:30:34.140
Home being Poland in this case.
 

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:36.471
It's really interesting that
the technology is not of

00:30:36.471 --> 00:30:37.279
interest to her.
 

00:30:37.279 --> 00:30:40.536
She doesn't--in this case talk
about the wonderful new

00:30:40.536 --> 00:30:44.221
