that something happens up here

00:47:18.873 --> 00:47:22.766
and there's a lot of discussion
about that but once it becomes

00:47:22.766 --> 00:47:25.681
socially--
the idea is that once it

00:47:25.681 --> 00:47:29.039
reaches that 10% level,
it just falls down,

00:47:29.039 --> 00:47:31.670
fertility just falls down like
a stone.

00:47:31.670 --> 00:47:37.615
In this period,
up here you can get all kinds

00:47:37.615 --> 00:47:41.985
of economic levels,
that different economic groups

00:47:41.985 --> 00:47:45.695
are having different fertility,
different educational groups,

00:47:45.695 --> 00:47:48.469
difference between urban and
rural,

00:47:48.469 --> 00:47:51.489
difference in whether they're
agricultural or in an industry,

00:47:51.489 --> 00:47:53.710
and you can find all these
differences,

00:47:53.710 --> 00:47:58.150
but once this fertility thing
starts like this,

00:47:58.150 --> 00:47:59.469
everybody does it.
 

00:47:59.469 --> 00:48:00.920
What they call these
differentials,

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:04.965
these socio economic
differentials just disappear and

00:48:04.965 --> 00:48:09.556
a farmer is just as likely to be
limiting his fertility as a

00:48:09.556 --> 00:48:12.280
bourgeois person in the cities.
 

00:48:20.110 --> 00:48:24.188
If you try to think of how
rapidly the economic situation

00:48:24.188 --> 00:48:26.489
changes,
or how rapidly does education

00:48:26.489 --> 00:48:29.769
increase,
and you look at all the various

00:48:29.769 --> 00:48:32.344
variables,
none of them increase with this

00:48:32.344 --> 00:48:34.284
kind of rapidity,
none of them change with that

00:48:34.284 --> 00:48:35.670
kind of ability,
infant mortality,

00:48:35.670 --> 00:48:37.190
almost anything you can
measure,

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:43.579
nothing goes with that kind of
a rate.

00:48:43.579 --> 00:48:52.090
What goes with that kind of a
rate?

00:48:52.090 --> 00:48:53.210
A fad, a fashion.
 

00:49:11.039 --> 00:49:14.594
If you look all around Europe,
and this was in your reading,

00:49:14.594 --> 00:49:18.090
what you see is the date of the
beginning of the decade.

00:49:18.090 --> 00:49:24.690
This is the decade where that
10% level was reached and what

00:49:24.690 --> 00:49:27.039
provinces are this?
 

00:49:27.039 --> 00:49:28.050
This is all France.
 

00:49:28.050 --> 00:49:31.010
Then there's a long delay,
a surprisingly long delay,

00:49:31.010 --> 00:49:35.920
and boom all the rest of Europe
then does it in basically--

00:49:35.920 --> 00:49:40.679
most of it's done between 1870
and 1930,

00:49:40.679 --> 00:49:42.010
it's almost all done.
 

00:49:42.010 --> 00:49:44.235
This just sweeps through
Europe, and again as I've showed

00:49:44.235 --> 00:49:46.081
you on the maps,
it includes Russia,

00:49:46.081 --> 00:49:49.358
Eastern Europe,
economically and educationally

00:49:49.358 --> 00:49:52.268
very underdeveloped kinds of
places,

00:49:52.268 --> 00:49:56.469
and yet the fertility drops,
this is all of Europe,

00:49:56.469 --> 00:49:58.139
nobody is left out.
 

00:49:58.139 --> 00:50:04.740
Again, it makes it difficult to
put an economic or an

00:50:04.740 --> 00:50:11.090
educational, any of these other
variables on it.

00:50:11.090 --> 00:50:15.221
What you have instead is,
and one of these stories you

00:50:15.221 --> 00:50:19.137
read about in your reading--
remember that each of these

00:50:19.137 --> 00:50:22.699
graduate students and post docs
was put on a different country

00:50:22.699 --> 00:50:24.920
of Europe in the Princeton
project.

00:50:24.920 --> 00:50:27.239
One had to do England,
one had to do--

00:50:27.239 --> 00:50:29.561
and have the who did England is
going to be guest lecturer here

00:50:29.561 --> 00:50:30.849
next week,
next Thursday,

00:50:30.849 --> 00:50:34.045
he's not going to talk about
that because you'll have had

00:50:34.045 --> 00:50:35.530
enough of that by then.
 

00:50:35.530 --> 00:50:39.110
There was a guy who was
assigned Spain;

00:50:39.110 --> 00:50:43.449
this guy is William Leisure,
and this I think you read a

00:50:43.449 --> 00:50:44.949
little bit about.
 

00:50:44.949 --> 00:50:48.291
He gathered all this data,
a huge amount of work in all

00:50:48.291 --> 00:50:52.005
the Spanish archives of every
province from going way back to

00:50:52.005 --> 00:50:54.833
1830 or something,
whatever was there,

00:50:54.833 --> 00:50:55.869
he looked at.
 

00:50:55.869 --> 00:51:00.079
And he put it all together and
he could not make any sense out

00:51:00.079 --> 00:51:01.389
of it whatsoever.
 

00:51:01.389 --> 00:51:05.360
This guy was going out of his
mind and he took to drawing a

00:51:05.360 --> 00:51:08.126
map of fertility rates,
sort of like those kinds of

00:51:08.126 --> 00:51:11.353
maps I just showed you,
fertility rates at different

00:51:11.353 --> 00:51:15.650
points in time in the different
provinces of Spain.

00:51:15.650 --> 00:51:18.900
He showed it to everybody and
apparently he was walking around

00:51:18.900 --> 00:51:21.992
campus one day and he saw a
professor of Spanish Literature

00:51:21.992 --> 00:51:25.297
who he had met somewhere and he
said he buttonholed the guy and

00:51:25.297 --> 00:51:27.429
showed him these graphs and
said,

00:51:27.429 --> 00:51:30.766
'I can't make any sense out of
this,' and he told the professor

00:51:30.766 --> 00:51:31.518
what it was.
 

00:51:31.518 --> 00:51:34.740
The professor said,
'That's the linguistic regions

00:51:34.740 --> 00:51:35.530
of Spain.'
 

00:51:35.530 --> 00:51:39.789
As you know Spain had a variety
of kingdoms,

00:51:39.789 --> 00:51:43.900
they were controlled by the
Muslims,

00:51:43.900 --> 00:51:46.929
and then the Northern
Christians kicked them out,

00:51:46.929 --> 00:51:51.284
but there's Castille and
Navarra, and Aragon and all of

00:51:51.284 --> 00:51:53.219
these cultural things.
 

00:51:53.219 --> 00:51:55.869
And still the Basques consider
themselves quite separate,

00:51:55.869 --> 00:51:58.239
the Catalans consider
themselves separate,

00:51:58.239 --> 00:52:02.199
so Spain, to this day,
has serious regional

00:52:02.199 --> 00:52:03.518
diversities.
 

00:52:03.518 --> 00:52:08.460
What apparently Leisure had
come up with unknowingly was a

00:52:08.460 --> 00:52:13.748
map of the linguistic boundaries
of ancient medieval Spain and

00:52:13.748 --> 00:52:15.829
they still remained.
 

00:52:15.829 --> 00:52:18.719
The idea that he came up with,
as well as is fairly obvious,

00:52:18.719 --> 00:52:20.630
is that people that could speak
the same language,

00:52:20.630 --> 00:52:23.365
the same dialect,
were of the common culture

00:52:23.365 --> 00:52:27.056
would talk to each other and
that it was social spread what

00:52:27.056 --> 00:52:30.871
kept the province,
a linguistic region uniform in

00:52:30.871 --> 00:52:34.789
its fertility practices was the
cultural spread,

00:52:34.789 --> 00:52:38.905
but that was the cultural unit
as well as the linguistic unit

00:52:38.905 --> 00:52:41.170
and it didn't cross boundaries.
 

00:52:41.170 --> 00:52:45.800
Another more quantified example
of that is Belgium and here is

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:50.130
Belgium, in Belgium they speak
two languages which are?

00:52:50.130 --> 00:52:53.804
French and Flemish,
and Flemish is almost the same

00:52:53.804 --> 00:52:54.179
as?
 

00:52:54.179 --> 00:52:56.440
Dutch, which is almost the same
as?

00:52:56.440 --> 00:53:00.391
German, so it's a big divide,
it's a Germanic/Romance

00:53:00.391 --> 00:53:01.760
language divide.
 

00:53:01.760 --> 00:53:06.786
This is a big language divide
and in Belgium here are the

00:53:06.786 --> 00:53:11.135
various provinces of Belgium,
and these are the southern ones

00:53:11.135 --> 00:53:13.059
near--
France is over here--so these

00:53:13.059 --> 00:53:15.800
are all French speaking and
Holland is up there,

00:53:15.800 --> 00:53:19.592
and Germany is over here--these
are the Flemish speaking

00:53:19.592 --> 00:53:20.420
provinces.
 

00:53:23.989 --> 00:53:32.909
When you look at their
fertility what happens is that--

00:53:46.619 --> 00:53:49.409
when you look at their
fertility France is,

00:53:49.409 --> 00:53:52.199
as you've heard 100 times,
starts the fertility

00:53:52.199 --> 00:53:54.789
transition,
fertility drops there.

00:53:54.789 --> 00:53:58.829
It goes--it takes a fair amount
of time but it goes first into

00:53:58.829 --> 00:54:02.471
French speaking Belgium and
French speaking Belgium then

00:54:02.471 --> 00:54:04.590
conforms to the French norm.
 

00:54:04.590 --> 00:54:09.831
Then there's this language line
and you compare across that line

00:54:09.831 --> 00:54:14.907
and nothing north of the line
changes and it takes 60 years to

00:54:14.907 --> 00:54:18.820
cross that language line that I
showed you.

00:54:37.239 --> 00:54:40.900
It takes 60 takes to cross the
language barrier.

00:54:40.900 --> 00:54:44.268
This guy Lesthaeghe,
the guy who studied--

00:54:44.268 --> 00:54:47.989
who was assigned to Belgium,
and he is Belgian himself,

00:54:47.989 --> 00:54:49.539
he said well what could be
causing it,

00:54:49.539 --> 00:54:53.510
what are the differences
between north/south aside from

00:54:53.510 --> 00:54:54.320
language?
 

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:56.679
When he was doing it they
didn't really come up with

00:54:56.679 --> 00:54:58.090
this--
when he was originally--when he

00:54:58.090 --> 00:55:00.628
started it they didn't--
hadn't understood this cultural

00:55:00.628 --> 00:55:03.860
difference and so he's looking
at socioeconomic variables.

00:55:03.860 --> 00:55:08.199
And so he took villages across
that boundary line there,

00:55:08.199 --> 00:55:10.768
and you take no more than five
kilometers difference and he

00:55:10.768 --> 00:55:13.338
would take villages that were
matched: the soil was kind of

00:55:13.338 --> 00:55:15.534
the same,
the agricultural productivity

00:55:15.534 --> 00:55:18.762
was the same,
and every kind of socioeconomic

00:55:18.762 --> 00:55:23.512
variable that he could find was
not different across that line

00:55:23.512 --> 00:55:25.070
except fertility.
 

00:55:25.070 --> 00:55:29.447
That the northern line just had
an awful lot more children then

00:55:29.447 --> 00:55:32.414
south of the line,
French speaking Flemish

00:55:32.414 --> 00:55:35.255
speaking and presumably
eliminating all these

00:55:35.255 --> 00:55:38.675
socioeconomic variables by
comparing these neighboring

00:55:38.675 --> 00:55:41.840
towns all across Belgium from
east to west,

00:55:41.840 --> 00:55:46.782
all across this line he looked
at these kinds of paired

00:55:46.782 --> 00:55:47.789
villages.
 

00:55:47.789 --> 00:55:49.420
Well he said what was doing it?
 

00:55:49.420 --> 00:55:55.710
Well there's--so they started
thinking about cultural reasons,

00:55:55.710 --> 00:55:58.190
and at that time in Europe
there were two--

00:55:58.190 --> 00:56:01.775
democracy was still
fairly--real democracy was still

00:56:01.775 --> 00:56:06.204
fairly young but most everybody
had the vote and there was a lot

00:56:06.204 --> 00:56:09.929
of discussion about who would
control democracy,

00:56:09.929 --> 00:56:11.980
whether democracy was a good or
bad thing,

00:56:11.980 --> 00:56:15.329
so the suffrage,
the expanded kind of suffrage,

00:56:15.329 --> 00:56:18.967
they still had kings and all
that, but the power was being

00:56:18.967 --> 00:56:22.668
eroded by parliaments and there
were two sets of parties as

00:56:22.668 --> 00:56:25.030
really there still are in
Europe.

00:56:25.030 --> 00:56:29.429
One was the Catholic party,
the conservative party called--

00:56:29.429 --> 00:56:33.311
the other was the socialist
party's or the communist

00:56:33.311 --> 00:56:38.389
party's,
and anybody know what they're

00:56:38.389 --> 00:56:39.559
called?
 

00:56:39.559 --> 00:56:43.106
The Social Democrats and there
are a variety of names other

00:56:43.106 --> 00:56:45.353
parties--
the Christian Demo--the parties

00:56:45.353 --> 00:56:48.550
that are still named Christian
Democrats and Social Democrats.

00:56:48.550 --> 00:56:54.159
Like in Germany they pass the
premiership back and forth

00:56:54.159 --> 00:56:55.690
between them.
 

00:56:55.690 --> 00:56:59.438
That was established at this
time and it was considered a

00:56:59.438 --> 00:57:03.320
fairly good marker for what we
call secularization that how

00:57:03.320 --> 00:57:07.268
much a person was still
believing in the old morality,

00:57:07.268 --> 00:57:09.869
the old styled things was
religious,

00:57:09.869 --> 00:57:13.409
they would usually vote for the
Christian democrats.

00:57:13.409 --> 00:57:17.041
People that had undergone some
sort of a transition and now

00:57:17.041 --> 00:57:20.800
were buying socialist theory or
worker solidarity theory,

00:57:20.800 --> 00:57:27.056
or believed in unions would
vote the Democratic Socialist

00:57:27.056 --> 00:57:27.949
party.
 

00:57:27.949 --> 00:57:31.369
What he did,
he said, 'okay let's look at

00:57:31.369 --> 00:57:36.414
each of the provinces again,
this is a smaller grouping then

00:57:36.414 --> 00:57:39.920
province and see what their vote
is.'

00:57:39.920 --> 00:57:43.904
There's the Catholic party,
and this is the percentage of

00:57:43.904 --> 00:57:47.309
non-Catholic party,
and then he just compared this

00:57:47.309 --> 00:57:50.070
with how much their fertility
had declined,

00:57:50.070 --> 00:57:52.360
again, always within marriage.
 

00:57:52.360 --> 00:57:56.534
It turns out the more
non-Catholic they are the

00:57:56.534 --> 00:57:59.710
greater the decline in
fertility.

00:57:59.710 --> 00:58:04.092
It's kind of a backwards thing,
and very nice line of

00:58:04.092 --> 00:58:05.610
proportionality.
 

00:58:05.610 --> 00:58:08.072
This is an exact
proportionality and the points

00:58:08.072 --> 00:58:10.159
stick really very close to that
line;

00:58:10.159 --> 00:58:13.150
it's not hard to see what that
line is,

00:58:13.150 --> 00:58:17.268
and so people--what became
clear is that culturally people

00:58:17.268 --> 00:58:21.025
that were voting for the
Catholic party and therefore

00:58:21.025 --> 00:58:24.710
were in the older mode of
culture did not drop their

00:58:24.710 --> 00:58:26.590
fertility very much.
 

00:58:26.590 --> 00:58:30.369
People who were voting the
socialist,

00:58:30.369 --> 00:58:31.438
the left wing,
liberal whatever you want to

00:58:31.438 --> 00:58:34.405
call it,
had dropped their fertility by

00:58:34.405 --> 00:58:45.079
60% to 80%,
a huge drop in fertility.

00:58:45.079 --> 00:58:54.670
All right, these kinds of data
kept coming up.

00:58:54.670 --> 00:59:01.746
To conclude--the bottom line is
that in this Princeton project

00:59:01.746 --> 00:59:07.896
they just could not tie
fertility change to any of the

00:59:07.896 --> 00:59:12.190
standard socioeconomic
variables.

00:59:12.190 --> 00:59:14.960
Now the word socioeconomic,
I think, is a terrible word.

00:59:14.960 --> 00:59:17.949
What is not either socio or
economic?

00:59:17.949 --> 00:59:21.123
I always go around and ask
people descriptions of it and I

00:59:21.123 --> 00:59:24.130
think it basically means
anything you can quantify,

00:59:24.130 --> 00:59:26.876
and you get interesting
variables like education and

00:59:26.876 --> 00:59:29.730
we'll see this sort of
disastrously from understanding

00:59:29.730 --> 00:59:32.530
the situation when we come into
the third world.

00:59:32.530 --> 00:59:36.090
Education suits you for a
better job,

00:59:36.090 --> 00:59:38.090
especially women,
so when people get educated

00:59:38.090 --> 00:59:40.411
it's an economic variable
because it suits you for a

00:59:40.411 --> 00:59:42.222
better job,
you can get higher pay,

00:59:42.222 --> 00:59:44.860
it makes it more worth your
while to go out and work than

00:59:44.860 --> 00:59:46.320
stay home and have children.
 

00:59:46.320 --> 00:59:50.286
But, education also gives you a
window on the world and makes

00:59:50.286 --> 00:59:53.654
you more open to new ideas,
a greater sense of agency that

00:59:53.654 --> 00:59:56.329
you can talk back to your
husband or your mother-in-law,

00:59:56.329 --> 00:59:58.500
and so forth,
so a lot of the variables--

00:59:58.500 --> 01:00:01.851
you can't decide is this an
economic variable or a social

01:00:01.851 --> 01:00:02.510
variable?
 

01:00:02.510 --> 01:00:07.014
It's very unfortunate that they
use this term socioeconomic

01:00:07.014 --> 01:00:07.869
variable.
 

01:00:07.869 --> 01:00:11.878
But, I think it was early stage
in understanding the problem and

01:00:11.878 --> 01:00:14.360
they didn't know what to do
about it.

01:00:14.360 --> 01:00:17.405
Also another problem,
it's always in the social

01:00:17.405 --> 01:00:20.119
sciences when you try to do
these studies,

01:00:20.119 --> 01:00:23.630
getting the data itself is
really very difficult.

01:00:23.630 --> 01:00:26.735
Since Europe is organized
politically into provinces

01:00:26.735 --> 01:00:29.719
that's where the data was
gathered and that's--

01:00:29.719 --> 01:00:33.253
they had province level things,
they didn't have individual

01:00:33.253 --> 01:00:36.820
village level information,
they didn't have individual

01:00:36.820 --> 01:00:38.690
family kind of information.
 

01:00:38.690 --> 01:00:42.440
When you do an aggregation,
even as finely as they could

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:44.472
do,
I mean it's amazing to do every

01:00:44.472 --> 01:00:46.619
province in Europe so that was
for the--

01:00:46.619 --> 01:00:50.461
for that period of social
science that was the low level

01:00:50.461 --> 01:00:53.934
of aggregation,
but still within each province

01:00:53.934 --> 01:00:58.809
you have a huge range of people
in very different circumstances,

01:00:58.809 --> 01:01:02.409
and maybe you're missing a lot
by this aggregation,

01:01:02.409 --> 01:01:05.070
so aggregation is a problem.
 

01:01:05.070 --> 01:01:08.545
Since this period a lot of
social science scholars have

01:01:08.545 --> 01:01:11.507
come back and argued
tremendously over this and

01:01:11.507 --> 01:01:14.623
saying,
'no there really are economic

01:01:14.623 --> 01:01:19.635
reasons for fertility decline,'
and we'll talk about those in a

01:01:19.635 --> 01:01:21.010
later lecture.
 

01:01:21.010 --> 01:01:24.711
I just want to summarize--we
spent a lot of time on this

01:01:24.711 --> 01:01:27.539
demographic transition and it's
theory,

01:01:27.539 --> 01:01:30.119
and a lot of reading--and every
year students say,

01:01:30.119 --> 01:01:33.762
'oh I hated that part of the
course,' but it is in a sense

01:01:33.762 --> 01:01:35.543
the most--
for the modern times it's the

01:01:35.543 --> 01:01:37.500
most important part of the
course because everything else

01:01:37.500 --> 01:01:39.824
that you read,
every understanding of the

01:01:39.824 --> 01:01:43.411
what's happening now in
developing countries is based on

01:01:43.411 --> 01:01:45.463
this stuff,
either agrees with it or

01:01:45.463 --> 01:01:47.807
disagrees with it,
or uses the same methodology or

01:01:47.807 --> 01:01:50.659
very self consciously tries to
use a different methodology,

01:01:50.659 --> 01:01:52.340
this is the foundation of the
fields.

01:01:52.340 --> 01:01:54.920
That's one reason you should
know about it.

01:01:54.920 --> 01:01:57.893
The other is it's such a
tremendous change,

01:01:57.893 --> 01:02:01.009
it may be to my mind,
it's the most important

01:02:01.009 --> 01:02:03.630
revolution ever in human
history.

01:02:03.630 --> 01:02:06.230
Look what happens throughout
this period.

01:02:06.230 --> 01:02:09.753
Life, people get to live three
times as long,

01:02:09.753 --> 01:02:14.239
imagine if you're at 20,
how many of you are under 20?

01:02:14.239 --> 01:02:17.891
Okay, half of you would be
dead, half of this class would

01:02:17.891 --> 01:02:21.282
be dead if we weren't--if we
hadn't gone through this

01:02:21.282 --> 01:02:23.369
transition of modernization.
 

01:02:23.369 --> 01:02:25.369
He's happy about that.
 

01:02:25.369 --> 01:02:28.349
The numbers of human beings,
the number of people that we

01:02:28.349 --> 01:02:31.010
now are able to keep alive is
ten times larger,

01:02:31.010 --> 01:02:33.840
everyday it gets bigger,
but last time I counted ten

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:37.340
times larger than what we think
the population was back then.

01:02:37.340 --> 01:02:40.596
So an enormous--even though
it's the introduction of

01:02:40.596 --> 01:02:44.300
contraception which limits the
amount of people or tries to

01:02:44.300 --> 01:02:46.280
limit the amount of people.
 

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:50.219
In fact, the number of people
on earth has just expanded

01:02:50.219 --> 01:02:54.590
enormously, both in numbers and
in how long each one lives.

01:02:54.590 --> 01:02:56.300
Wealth, individual per capita
wealth,

01:02:56.300 --> 01:02:59.914
we saw that the industrial
revolution by itself got into

01:02:59.914 --> 01:03:04.579
Malthusian problems and didn't,
at least up until the fertility

01:03:04.579 --> 01:03:07.909
transition,
did not improve people's

01:03:07.909 --> 01:03:09.739
individual wealth.
 

01:03:09.739 --> 01:03:13.507
That required the combination
of industrial revolution which

01:03:13.507 --> 01:03:16.893
increased production and
fertility control which put a

01:03:16.893 --> 01:03:20.534
limit on the number of people
trying to get advantage from

01:03:20.534 --> 01:03:22.579
that increased production.
 

01:03:22.579 --> 01:03:25.340
We've seen a tremendous
democratization of marriage.

01:03:25.340 --> 01:03:29.411
Imagine a society where 30%
of--70% of the people are

01:03:29.411 --> 01:03:31.864
unmarried,
we sort of talk a lot about

01:03:31.864 --> 01:03:35.000
marriage and how marriage is
going away as an institution.

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:36.469
We're way, way ahead of that.
 

01:03:36.469 --> 01:03:41.039
China is way ahead of that and
so imagine there was that--

01:03:41.039 --> 01:03:44.063
very few of you would have
prospects of ever getting

01:03:44.063 --> 01:03:47.619
married because society just
didn't allow it and the same for

01:03:47.619 --> 01:03:52.289
sex as I've mentioned,
the democratization of sex.

01:03:52.289 --> 01:03:54.960
Your fertility coming under
your individual control,

01:03:54.960 --> 01:03:57.838
what a big change in life,
that you, now it's one of the

01:03:57.838 --> 01:03:59.409
big decision you can make.
 

01:03:59.409 --> 01:04:01.875
Do I want some children,
many children,

01:04:01.875 --> 01:04:04.860
few children,
whatever, when do I want them?

01:04:04.860 --> 01:04:07.809
All this comes under control.
 

01:04:07.809 --> 01:04:10.556
Within marriage,
previously couples were

01:04:10.556 --> 01:04:14.639
constantly under the pressure of
constant childbearing,

01:04:14.639 --> 01:04:17.199
that the wife was always either
pregnant or lactating.

01:04:17.199 --> 01:04:20.887
Later I'll show you some
statistics from the third world

01:04:20.887 --> 01:04:24.510
that women are almost never
free, they're always either

01:04:24.510 --> 01:04:27.260
pregnant or lactating until they
die.

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:30.755
Men had to go out--this is a
period when men were basically

01:04:30.755 --> 01:04:31.900
the breadwinners.
 

01:04:31.900 --> 01:04:35.420
They had to support an ever
increasing number of children

01:04:35.420 --> 01:04:38.000
under difficult economic
circumstances.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.929
So men and women were freed
from the requirement--

01:04:40.929 --> 01:04:43.840
they had no choice--the
requirement of supporting,

01:04:43.840 --> 01:04:46.889
taking care of and supporting
these large families.

01:04:46.889 --> 01:04:51.630
There's so many issues that
changed during this time.

01:04:51.630 --> 01:04:55.110
If you--if any of you are
thinking of doing term papers

01:04:55.110 --> 01:04:58.914
there's just an infinite number
of things that have not even

01:04:58.914 --> 01:05:00.139
been looked at.
 

01:05:00.139 --> 01:05:02.612
For instance,
we talked a lot about

01:05:02.612 --> 01:05:05.449
abandonment of children,
infanticide.

01:05:05.449 --> 01:05:08.570
When do you think that
disappeared?

01:05:08.570 --> 01:05:11.949
Something in about this time;
you read about it into the

01:05:11.949 --> 01:05:14.130
1800s there was a lot of it and
then it goes away.

01:05:14.130 --> 01:05:17.903
There's a lot written about the
period when it was heavy and not

01:05:17.903 --> 01:05:21.139
much understanding of why did
infanticide disappear.

01:05:21.139 --> 01:05:22.519
Was it due to this?
 

01:05:22.519 --> 01:05:25.583
I don't know the answer;
I don't think it has been

01:05:25.583 --> 01:05:27.626
discovered;
investigated,

01:05:27.626 --> 01:05:29.039
a great term paper.
 

01:05:29.039 --> 01:05:32.349
What about the romantic
conception of marriage?

01:05:32.349 --> 01:05:35.077
When marriage changes like this
it becomes less of an economic

01:05:35.077 --> 01:05:36.766
thing,
less of a childbearing thing,

01:05:36.766 --> 01:05:38.320
you don't need your wife to
work,

01:05:38.320 --> 01:05:41.590
especially on the farm.
 

01:05:41.590 --> 01:05:45.322
What is the tie in between
romantic conceptions that we all

01:05:45.322 --> 01:05:49.121
now have about marriage and love
and all that and this whole

01:05:49.121 --> 01:05:50.860
demographic transition?
 

01:05:50.860 --> 01:05:55.110
In almost every way you can
think of modern culture,

01:05:55.110 --> 01:05:58.777
this is at the root of it,
that this is a thing that you

01:05:58.777 --> 01:06:02.179
always have to consider as
whatever you believe,

01:06:02.179 --> 01:06:05.367
however you're leading your
life, how much of it is due to

01:06:05.367 --> 01:06:08.833
these pioneers that we've talked
about that started controlling

01:06:08.833 --> 01:06:12.021
their fertility as an individual
decision rather than as a

01:06:12.021 --> 01:06:13.420
community decision?
 

